<!-- ── FAQ ── -->
<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>FAQ</h2>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      How to calculate percentage of a number?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        Multiply the number by the percentage and divide by 100. For example, 25% of 80: 80 &times; 25 &divide; 100 = 20. A shortcut: move the decimal point of the percentage two places left and multiply. 25% becomes 0.25, and 0.25 &times; 80 = 20.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      How to find what percentage one number is of another?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        Divide the part by the whole and multiply by 100. For example, what percentage is 45 of 180? 45 &divide; 180 &times; 100 = 25%. Think of it as "part over whole, times 100."
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      How to calculate percentage increase?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        Subtract the old value from the new value, divide by the old value, and multiply by 100. Formula: (New &minus; Old) &divide; Old &times; 100. For example, a price going from $50 to $65: (65 &minus; 50) &divide; 50 &times; 100 = 30% increase.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      Can percentage change be negative?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        Yes — a negative percentage change means a decrease. If a stock price goes from $100 to $80, that's (80 &minus; 100) &divide; 100 &times; 100 = &minus;20%. The calculator will show this as a "20% decrease."
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      What's the difference between percentage and percentage points?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        This is a common source of confusion. If an interest rate goes from 5% to 7%, that's an increase of 2 <strong>percentage points</strong> but a 40% <strong>percentage increase</strong> (because 2 &divide; 5 &times; 100 = 40%). Percentage points measure the absolute difference between two percentages. Percentage change measures the relative change. News headlines often mix these up.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

